recordings.loc: Colosó, Sucre
recordings.file-name: XC360730-COLOM Syristes song bbwr myst 170220 orig NK.mp3
recordings.rmk: Recording unmodified. Habitat was a strip of gallery forest along the Arroyo de Colosó, that winds through farmland in a region of low hills with dry scrub forest. The main mystery song in this clip starts with a whistle similar to Sibilant Sirystes (from east Brazil) followed by loud chips like Western Sirystes (from Darien region of Panama and points south in west Colombia). Is this really a Sirystes, and if so, which one? It doesn't fit vocally with other populations. [Update 12/24/2019: I now recognize this vocalization as call and partial song of Olive-sided Flycatcher, a local winter resident.]

recordings.rmk:
Audio was not modified.

Sound ID: Olive-sided Flycatcher-0sec; Hermit Thrush-12sec; Pine Siskin-32sec; Mountain Chickadee-37sec; Black-capped Chickadee-1:26; Yellow-rumped Warbler-2:03;

Habitat: subalpine; Engleman Spruce-Subalpine Fir Forest ecosystem surrounding a clearcut.

Behavior-the flycatcher remained inside the crown of a tall aspen tree inside a clearcut while a young Red-tailed Hawk hunted it. The hawk soon gave up its predatory plan.

Nonetheless, I observed Olive-sided Flycatcher at every clearcut along this logging road.

recordings.rmk: Part of a LONG series of 'pip-pip' calls with many 'peer-pip' calls mixed in. The BNA account notes this as being given by the male, but not clear if that has really been confirmed. Wright (cited in the BNA account) did study marked birds in Alaska and confirmed females singing variations of the typical song, but didn't exactly describe this call. Since it resembles the last two notes of the typical song, I wonder if it MIGHT be female song. Pieplow notes this call given mainly in breeding season.

recordings.loc: Waterloo, Waterloo Regional Municipality, Ontario
recordings.rmk: This is two separate recordings paired back-to-back. Each recording has had the interval between vocalizations shortened significantly, as the recordings were made on the edge of a housing subdivision with interfering noises periodically in the background (as much of this as possible was spliced out). The bird itself was perched on a series of dead snags at a minimum distance of 50 m away (it moved around some during observation). The area is moderately wet, bog-like forest edge. The adjacent forest is a mixed-forest type with little to moderate interior disturbance, but surrounded by urban sprawl (sub-urban housing).
